#pad(left: 10%)[
    #text(weight: "bold")[Abstract]
    #linebreak()
    #text(size: 8pt)[
        #emph[La Ghigliottina], the final game of the Italian TV show #emph[L'Eredità], presents
        five clue words and asks for the single word that connects to all five. The connection is
        rarely plain semantic similarity: it is collocational and cultural, the solution forming a
        common multi-word expression with each clue. We build a #emph[typed], weighted word graph
        from the PAISÀ corpus, where edge types encode MWE-bearing syntactic patterns
        (noun--adjective, #emph[X e Y], #emph[X di Y], #emph[X da Y]) and edge weights are
        pattern-conditioned PPMI, and we fold in curated `IDIOM` edges mined from Italian
        #emph[polirematiche] and proverb lists. A simple flat PPMI-sum solver over this graph
        reaches #strong[accuracy\@1 0.31 / MRR 0.38] on the EVALITA 2018 NLP4FUN test set. We then
        document an extensive set of extensions that were explored and rejected: knowledge-graph
        embeddings, personalised PageRank, three additional corpora, compound / embedding-similarity /
        Wiktionary / ConceptNet edges, breadth-aware scorers, and a learned re-ranker. Every one of
        them improves recall or MRR but none improves accuracy\@1: the task is bottlenecked by
        register-matched recall, not by ranking sophistication.
    ]

    #v(4pt)
    #text(weight: "bold")[Keywords]
    #linebreak()
    #text(size: 8pt)[La Ghigliottina, language games, PPMI, collocations, multi-word expressions, EVALITA NLP4FUN]
]

