= Introduction and Motivations

#emph[La Ghigliottina] gives the player five clue words and asks for the one solution word
that links to all five simultaneously. The linking relation is almost never distributional
similarity; it is #emph[collocational and cultural]. The solution typically forms a fixed
multi-word expression (MWE), a compound, or an idiom with each clue: `capo`+`stazione` $->$
#emph[capostazione]; `sale` #emph[e] `pepe`; `acqua` #emph[di] `mare`; `sale` #emph[grosso].

The signal lives inside specific syntactic patterns rather than in a similarity space. Because
of this purely distributional models (word2vec/fastText) are a poor structural fit. For example,
a concrete test game like this:
#align(center)[
    `legno, forte, continua, malattia, veloce` $->$ `cassa`
]
would not be solved by a similarity-based embedding model.

The design question this project answers is therefore #emph[not] "which model is most powerful" but
"which #emph[signal] does the game actually rely on, and what is the smallest system that
captures it directly." The answer, established across many experiments, is that a plain typed
co-occurrence graph enriched with curated idiom edges captures it, and that the residual error
is a #emph[recall] problem, missing clue→ answer links, that no smarter scorer
can close.

This report describes the shipped system (Section 3), evaluates it (Section 4), and, because
the negative results are the substantive contribution, documents in Section 5 the full set of
extensions that were tried and did not move the top-1 metric. None of the Section 5 machinery
is part of the final codebase; it is retained here as the experimental record that justifies
the minimal design.

= Related Work

The EVALITA NLP4FUN shared task @basile2018nlp4fun framed #emph[La Ghigliottina] as a
computational language game. The seminal artificial player, OTTHO @basile2009ottho, solved it
by a #emph[knowledge-infusion] process over a dictionary, proverb lists, and Wikipedia:
retrieval / co-occurrence over large Italian text and lexical resources, an approach that
outperformed learned-embedding methods, the same qualitative outcome we reproduce here. Our
contribution is not a new model but a controlled ablation showing #emph[why]: on a graph of
~30k entities, knowledge-graph embeddings are dominated by hubness, and every
recall-broadening extension trades top-1 accuracy for rank-tail recall.

The strongest published player on this exact task is UNIOR4NLP, later released as
#emph[Il Mago della Ghigliottina] @sangati2018unior @sangati2020mago, which won the EVALITA
2018 NLP4FUN evaluation @basile2018nlp4fun and its 2020 successor Ghigliottin-AI
@basile2020ghigliottinai, reporting #strong[61.0% accuracy on the 2018 test set and 68.6% on
the 2020 set]. This project set out to #emph[replicate] that system and then extend it: its
MWE-based design is the starting point we deliberately mirror, sharing PAISÀ, the De Mauro
#emph[polirematiche] (30,633 MWE entries) and #emph[vocabolario di base], curated proverb
lists, `X+Y` compounds, and essentially the same six MWE-bearing patterns
(noun--adjective, `X e Y`, `X di Y`, `X (prep) (det) Y`, compounds) that we encode as typed
edges. The extensions in Section 5, knowledge-graph embeddings above all, were meant to push
#emph[past] their number. Neither goal succeeded: our reproduction on the same 2018 data reaches
only 0.31, and none of the extensions moved acc\@1. The shortfall is a coverage gap, not a
scoring one, their advantage comes from broader curated resources (itWaC, 1.5B words; Wikipedia
titles; morphologically expanded De Mauro entries; far larger proverb lists), which is precisely
the #emph[register-matched associative phrase resource] our error analysis (Section 5) isolates
as the one axis with demonstrated acc\@1 headroom. Falling short of their result is, in that
sense, the same finding read from the other side: on this game, coverage, not ranking, is the
binding constraint.

Methodologically the system rests on pointwise mutual information (PMI) and its positive
variant (PPMI), the standard association measure for collocations, applied #emph[within]
each syntactic relation rather than over a single undifferentiated co-occurrence window.
Because the game's signal is syntagmatic rather than paradigmatic, purely distributional
embeddings, word2vec @mikolov2013efficient and fastText
@bojanowski2017enriching @grave2018learning, are a poor structural fit, a hypothesis the
knowledge-graph-embedding experiments (Section 5) confirm.

= Proposed Approach

== Description of the solution and dataset

The shipped solver has three stages.

+ #emph[Build a typed, weighted word graph] from the PAISÀ corpus. Edge types are
  MWE-bearing relations extracted by adjacency patterns over lemma+POS sequences:
  `MOD` (noun-adjective, either order), `BINOMIAL` (`X e Y`), `DI` (`X di Y`), and
  `DA` (`X da Y`). Edge weights are pattern-conditioned PPMI: PMI is computed
  within each relation's own pair population, so the association of a pair is measured
  against the right baseline rather than a global one.

+ #emph[Fold in curated `IDIOM` edges] mined from Italian #emph[polirematiche] and proverb
  lists. These supply the clue $->$ answer links that running-text adjacency patterns
  structurally cannot produce (idioms are phrase lists, not local syntactic patterns). Each
  curated edge is added with a constant weight (default 5.5, the single tuned scalar of the
  system; see @sec:idiom-weight).

+ #emph[Solve with flat PPMI-sum.] For each clue, take the strongest edge to a candidate
  (a `max` over relations and directions, computed once as an adjacency map), then #emph[sum]
  those best-edge weights across the five clues. The candidate with the highest sum is the
  predicted solution.

#strong[Dataset.] Evaluation uses the EVALITA 2018 NLP4FUN test set: 100 games in JSON-Lines,
each with `hint1..hint5` and a gold `sol`. This set is used for scoring only, never for
training, the solver has no learned parameters.

== Main technical details

#strong[Corpus.] The base graph is built from the full PAISÀ corpus @lyding2014paisa
(annotated CoNLL, CC BY-NC-SA), streamed rather than materialised. The loader (`corpus.py`) reads gzip/xz
transparently, maps both the Tanl and Universal Dependencies POS tagsets to a coarse common
set, falls back from a missing lemma to the surface form, and yields one sentence at a time so
that memory is bounded by vocabulary size, not corpus size.

#strong[Vocabulary.] A frequency list defines the candidate vocabulary: the top $approx 50,000$
lemmas with frequency ≥ 5. Only pairs whose #emph[both] endpoints are in this
vocabulary are counted.

#strong[Pair extraction and PPMI]. For each sentence the extractor walks tokens
and emits: a `MOD` pair for adjacent NOUN–ADJ; and, for tokens two apart joined
by the right function word, a `BINOMIAL` / `DI` / `DA` pair keyed on
the connective lemma and POS. For each relation, the weight of its edge follows these
computations
$
    p(h, t | r) &= c(h, t, r) / "tot"(r) \
    p(h | r) &= sum_(t') c(h, t', r) / "tot"(r) \
    p(t | r) &= sum_(h') c(h', t, r) / "tot"(r) \
    "pmi"(h, t | r) &= ln( p(h, t | r) / (p(h | r) p(t | r)) ) = \
    &= ln( (c(h, t, r) dot.c "tot"(r)) / (sum_(t') c(h, t', r) dot.c sum_(h') c(h', t, r)) ) \
    "ppmi"(h, t | r) &= max(0, "pmi"(h, t | r))

$
where $h$ is the head lemma, $t$ the tail lemma, $r$ the relation, and $c(h, t, r)$ is the
count of the triple. The total count $"tot"(r)$ is the sum of all counts for that relation.

Each weight is kept only when $c(h, t, r) ≥ 5$ (`min_count`). The curated idiom edges are
then merged in as a separate `IDIOM` relation at constant weight.

#strong[Curated idiom mining]. Three Italian resources, 31k De
Mauro #emph[polirematiche], 4.7k tagged #emph[polirematiche], and 369 proverbs, are tagged
with spaCy @honnibal2020spacy (`it_core_news_sm`); only #emph[nominal] content lemmas (NOUN/ADJ/PROPN) that are in
the vocabulary are kept, and an undirected edge is emitted for every unordered lemma pair
co-occurring in a phrase. Restricting to nominal lemmas is deliberate: including VERB/ADV
pulls in hub lemmas (#emph[fare], #emph[avere], #emph[essere]) that pollute the sum scorer.
The 36k phrases yield $approx$ 18.5k distinct nominal pairs.

== Optional solution explanation <sec:describe>

Beyond predicting the solution, the system can optionally #emph[explain] it. Given the
predicted answer and the five clues, a small instruction-tuned LLM, Qwen3-1.7B
@qwenteam2025qwen3 run locally through the Hugging Face `transformers` pipeline, is prompted
in Italian to produce one sentence per clue naming the multi-word expression, compound, or
idiom that links it to the answer (greedy decoding, thinking mode disabled). This is a post-hoc
presentation layer, exposed via `--describe`; it plays no part in solving and does not affect
the ranking metrics.

= Evaluation

== Setup and metrics

The graph is built from full PAISÀ (599,964 typed triples over 32,018 entities at
`min_count=5`, top-50k vocabulary). We report, over the 100-game EVALITA test set:
#emph[found] (gold present in the top 100), MRR, and accuracy\@{1,5,10,100}. The primary
metric for the game is accuracy\@1.

== Main result

#figure(
  caption: [The shipped configuration against the plain baseline. Curated idiom edges are the
    single largest lever in the project.],
  table(
    columns: 7,
    align: (left, center, center, center, center, center, center),
    stroke: (x: none),
    table.hline(),
    table.header[Configuration][found][MRR][acc\@1][acc\@5][acc\@10][acc\@100],
    table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
    [flat-PPMI(sum), PAISÀ only], [60], [0.2881], [0.240], [0.330], [0.380], [0.600],
    [#strong[flat-PPMI(sum) + IDIOM (w=5.5)]], [#strong[67]], [#strong[0.3841]], [#strong[0.310]],
      [#strong[0.480]], [#strong[0.520]], [#strong[0.670]],
    table.hline(),
  ),
)

Curated idiom edges lift accuracy\@1 from 0.240 to #strong[0.310] (+29% relative) and MRR from
0.288 to 0.384. The idiom weight (5.5) is the system's only tuned scalar, selected on the
#emph[train] split (@sec:idiom-weight), and it sits on a wide inverted-U plateau rather than a
knife-edge fit. A constant weight beats scaling by how many phrases share a pair:
the game draws on rare expressions, so uniform trust wins.

== Idiom weight tuning <sec:idiom-weight>

The constant `IDIOM` edge weight is the only free scalar in the system, and it is tuned on the
#emph[train] split (965 EVALITA games), never on the 100-game test set used for the results
above. The sweep is run by `tools/idiom_tune.py`, which rebuilds the merged graph at each weight
and evaluates the flat PPMI-sum solver on train, parallelising the 21 weights across worker
processes. Accuracy\@1 traces a clean inverted-U, rising from 0.167 at #emph[w] = 0 (idioms off)
to a peak of #strong[0.263 at #emph[w] = 5.5] and decaying gently thereafter as over-weighted
flat idiom edges start to outrank genuine PPMI collocations.

#figure(
  caption: [Train-set accuracy\@1 as a function of the constant `IDIOM` edge weight
    (`tools/idiom_tune.py`, 965 train games, PAISÀ+IDIOM graph). The peak (marked) is at
    #emph[w] = 5.5, on a broad plateau spanning #emph[w] = 5--7.],
  {
    let ws = (0.0,0.5,1.0,1.5,2.0,2.5,3.0,3.5,4.0,4.5,5.0,5.5,6.0,6.5,7.0,7.5,8.0,8.5,9.0,9.5,10.0)
    let accs = (0.1668,0.1699,0.1741,0.1824,0.1938,0.2021,0.2145,0.2218,0.2352,0.2456,0.2580,0.2632,0.2601,0.2591,0.2580,0.2477,0.2404,0.2311,0.2290,0.2259,0.2259)
    lq.diagram(
      width: 11cm, height: 4.6cm,
      xlabel: [`IDIOM` edge weight],
      ylabel: [train acc\@1],
      lq.plot(ws, accs, mark: "o", mark-size: 3.5pt, stroke: rgb("#1f4e79")),
      lq.plot((5.5,), (0.2632,), mark: "o", mark-size: 7pt, stroke: none, color: red),
    )
  },
)

The plateau is wide (#emph[w] = 5--7 all stay within 0.005 of the peak), so the exact value is
not delicate; 5.5 is adopted as the shipped default. The absolute numbers are lower than the
test-set results because the train split is larger and harder, but the tuning is what matters:
the weight is fixed from train and carried over unchanged to test.

== Description quality

The optional explanation pass (@sec:describe) is scored against the gold `desc` field of the
100 test games. Each explanation is generated for the solver's #emph[own] top-1 prediction, so
the numbers fold in solver errors as well as phrasing differences.

#figure(
  caption: [Explanation quality of the Qwen3-1.7B `--describe` pass against the gold `desc`
    field (100 test games). BLEU is on the sacreBLEU 0--100 scale; the rest are 0--1.],
  table(
    columns: 6,
    align: (center, center, center, center, center, center),
    stroke: (x: none),
    table.hline(),
    table.header[BLEU][ROUGE-1][ROUGE-2][ROUGE-L][ROUGE-Lsum][BERTScore],
    table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
    [1.70], [0.248], [0.035], [0.177], [0.170], [0.658],
    table.hline(),
  ),
)

The low n-gram overlap (BLEU 1.70, ROUGE-L 0.18) is expected: the explanations are free-form
generative Italian that rarely reuses the gold wording, and roughly two thirds of them describe
a predicted word that differs from the gold (acc\@1 0.31). #emph[BERTScore] 0.66, which measures
contextual-embedding similarity rather than surface overlap, confirms the explanations are
semantically on-topic.

= Explored Extensions and Negative Results

This section documents the extensions that were built, evaluated, and then left out of
the final system. They are the experimental core of the project: they establish that
accuracy\@1 0.31 is a genuine ceiling for this signal, and that the residual error is a recall
problem. The recurring pattern is stated once and confirmed repeatedly: #emph[every lever
improves recall / MRR / acc\@{10,100} but not acc\@1.]

== Knowledge-graph embeddings (the original thesis) -- decisive loss

The project's original hypothesis was that learned KG embeddings could score #emph[unobserved]
clue$->$solution links that a graph baseline cannot. Trained with PyKEEN @ali2021pykeen over the
same typed triples, ComplEx @trouillon2016complex and RotatE @sun2019rotate lost badly.

#figure(
  caption: [KGE and PageRank vs. the flat baseline (PAISÀ only, all candidates).],
  table(
    columns: 7,
    align: (left, center, center, center, center, center, center),
    stroke: (x: none),
    table.hline(),
    table.header[Method][found][MRR][acc\@1][acc\@5][acc\@10][acc\@100],
    table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
    [flat-PPMI(sum)], [60], [0.2881], [#strong[0.240]], [0.330], [0.380], [0.600],
    [PageRank (personalised)], [46], [0.0829], [0.050], [0.110], [0.160], [0.460],
    [KGE ComplEx (full, 300 ep)], [21], [0.0230], [0.010], [0.030], [0.040], [0.210],
    [KGE RotatE (full, 150 ep, 16 negs)], [37], [0.0676], [0.040], [0.080], [0.100], [0.370],
    table.hline(),
  ),
)

A head-ranking sanity check explains the collapse: for known MWE partners, RotatE ranks the
true head at ~\#66--170. Over ~30k entities, link prediction is
dominated by hubness, frequent adjectives and prepositions absorb probability mass
so the model smears its score instead of pinning the collocate. This reproduces the EVALITA
finding that co-occurrence methods beat learned embeddings on this game.

== Candidate restriction and breadth-aware scorers

#emph[Noun-restriction] (restrict candidates to noun-dominant lemmas) hurts:
MRR 0.288 → 0.236, found 60 → 55. The sum scorer already ranks the true
noun above adjective distractors, so the restriction only drops recall.

The game's rule is that the answer connects to all five clues, which motivates scorers
that reward breadth over a single strong edge. Both hurt top-1:

#figure(
  caption: [Breadth-aware scorers on the PAISÀ+IDIOM champion graph.],
  table(
    columns: 7,
    align: (left, center, center, center, center, center, center),
    stroke: (x: none),
    table.hline(),
    table.header[Scorer][found][MRR][acc\@1][acc\@5][acc\@10][acc\@100],
    table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
    [#strong[sum (champion)]], [67], [#strong[0.3841]], [#strong[0.310]], [0.480], [0.520], [0.670],
    [coverage (count clues covered)], [65], [0.2867], [0.200], [0.400], [0.500], [0.650],
    [logsum (diminishing returns)], [68], [0.3783], [0.290], [0.480], [0.570], [0.680],
    table.hline(),
  ),
)

PPMI magnitude pins top-1; rewarding breadth dilutes it. Coverage-first is worst
(0.310$->$0.200): edge existence is noisy (hub adjectives, flat-weight idiom
edges all count as "covered"), so weak-but-complete junk outranks strong-but-partial truth.
`logsum` softens this but still trades acc\@1 for recall. (`sum` is the shipped default; the
alternatives remain selectable via `--combine` but are not recommended.)

== Additional corpora -- register beats volume

Three further corpora were joined into the PPMI scan. The lesson is that #emph[register], not
volume, is the lever, and that candidate vocabulary must stay PAISÀ-defined while an extra
corpus only enriches counts.

#figure(
  caption: [Corpus joins, flat-PPMI(sum) with PAISÀ-defined candidates.],
  table(
    columns: 8,
    align: (left, center, center, center, center, center, center, left),
    stroke: (x: none),
    table.hline(),
    table.header[Added corpus][+tokens][found][MRR][acc\@1][acc\@10][acc\@100][verdict],
    table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
    [-- (PAISÀ only)], [--], [60], [0.2881], [0.240], [0.380], [0.600], [baseline],
    [Wikipedia (CoNLL'17)], [+650M], [61], [0.2854], [0.240], [0.410], [0.610], [recall only],
    [OpenSubtitles 12M], [+85M], [63], [#strong[0.3193]], [#strong[0.270]], [0.420], [0.630], [#strong[helps]],
    [OpenSubtitles full], [+766M], [66], [0.3164], [0.250], [0.450], [0.660], [$arrow.t$ recall $arrow.b$ acc\@1],
    [itWaC (1 of 21 archives)], [+93M], [60], [0.2785], [0.220], [--], [0.600], [hurts],
    table.hline(),
  ),
)

#emph[OpenSubtitles] @lison2016opensubtitles (12M-line subset) is the only corpus join that
improves acc\@1 (0.240$->$0.270): register-matched dialogue sharpens the game's collocations
even though it barely grows the graph. #emph[Wikipedia] (CoNLL 2017 UD parse) doubled the graph
yet gave recall only because of its encyclopedic register. #emph[itWaC] @baroni2009wacky
(general web text, same register as PAISÀ) slightly hurt and the run was stopped after one archive.
Scaling OpenSubtitles to the full 766M tokens broadened recall but lowered acc\@1
to 0.250, more of the right register is not monotonically better, because extra collocations also
reinforce distractors at rank 1. Notably, none of these joins beats the curated idiom edges, and
stacking OpenSubtitles with idioms gives the best recall/MRR (found 70, acc\@100 0.70)
while acc\@1 (0.32) stays within noise of pure PAISÀ+IDIOM (0.31).

== Curated compound edges -- small recall gain, acc\@1 held

The headline #emph[capostazione] case is a single-token compound invisible to the adjacency
patterns. A heuristic decompounder (a node splits unambiguously into two other frequent
nominal nodes) produced 1,708 `COMPOUND` edges. On top of the champion this lifts found
67$->$69 and acc\@100 0.670$->$0.690 with acc\@1 steady at 0.310, a clean
but small recall gain. Kept out of the final system as marginal.

== The recall-miss anatomy -- why the ceiling exists

A gold-rank diagnostic on the champion graph partitions the 100 test games: #emph[31 already
rank \#1; 21 at rank 2--10; 17 at rank 11--100; 31 missing (>100, recall-dead).]
Raising the vocabulary from 50k to 100k adds zero new gold answers on test (98/100
gold are already nodes), this means that the bottleneck is not node coverage. Dumping the 31 missing games
shows the gold answer connects to 0 clues (10 games), 1 clue (18), or 2 clues (3): the sum
scorer cannot lift an answer with ≤ 2 weak edges over the flood that touch 3--5. The
missing links are #emph[syntagmatic collocations people simply know] (#emph[cassa forte /
continua / malattia], #emph[terza età], #emph[vita da cani]) plus a proper-noun residue. This
is precisely why similarity and association-based edges cannot help: the gap is associative
clue$→ $answer #emph[phrases], not synonyms.

== Off-corpus edge sources -- all the right idea, all too thin

Four external resources were folded in as new edge relations to attack the 31 recall-dead
games. Each is qualitatively the right kind of signal and quantitatively insufficient.

#figure(
  caption: [Off-corpus edge sources on the PAISÀ+IDIOM champion (test unless noted). The
    decisive number for a recall lever is #emph[found].],
  table(
    columns: 6,
    align: (left, left, center, center, center, left),
    stroke: (x: none),
    table.hline(),
    table.header[Source][edges][found][MRR][acc\@1][decisive result],
    table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
    [#emph[baseline]], [--], [67--69], [0.3841], [#strong[0.310]], [--],
    [SIM (fastText cc.it.300)], [$approx$268k], [67--68], [0.3993], [0.350], [train found 629$->$629],
    [Wiktionary MWEs (kaikki)], [21,358], [69], [0.3931], [0.310], [recovered 2 of 31; gate $>= 3$ fails],
    [ConceptNet 5.7 (IT)], [24,854], [67], [0.3841], [0.310], [train found 629$->$630],
    table.hline(),
  ),
)

#emph[SIM] (fastText @grave2018learning cosine neighbours) leaves `found` unchanged:
nearest neighbours are #emph[paradigmatic] (synonyms of already-connected words), not the
syntagmatic clue$→ $answer collocations needed, so they re-rank within reach instead
of extending it. It must be weighted below PPMI ($w <= 3$) or it floods every clue with
synonyms and demotes real answers.

#emph[Wiktionary MWEs] (via wiktextract @ylonen2022wiktextract) recovered exactly
2 of the 31 misses (13.9k phrases collapse to only $approx$2.9k net-new pairs after overlap
with De Mauro), failing a pre-registered "$>= 3$ recovered" gate.

#emph[ConceptNet] @speer2017conceptnet, an association KB by construction, bought exactly
one net-new reachable answer: Italian single-lemma coverage is too sparse.

== Learned re-ranker -- the ceiling is not a ranking artefact

The 18 mid-rank (2--10) games look like a re-ranking opportunity, and `train.json` (965 games)
had so far been used only to fit the single idiom-weight scalar (@sec:idiom-weight). We replaced
the scalar `sum` with a 10-feature linear scorer (`sum_ppmi`,
`coverage`, `max_edge`, `logsum`, and per-relation coverage) and fit the weights on
train and evaluated on test.

#figure(
  caption: [Learned re-ranker (coordinate ascent on train acc\@1) vs. the sum baseline.],
  table(
    columns: 7,
    align: (left, center, center, center, center, center, center),
    stroke: (x: none),
    table.hline(),
    table.header[Configuration][found][MRR][acc\@1][acc\@5][acc\@10][acc\@100],
    table.hline(stroke: 0.5pt),
    [sum (baseline), test], [69], [0.3841], [0.310], [0.480], [0.520], [0.690],
    [reranker, train (965)], [--], [--], [0.350], [--], [--], [--],
    [reranker, test], [#strong[70]], [#strong[0.4043]], [#strong[0.330]], [#strong[0.490]], [#strong[0.580]], [#strong[0.700]],
    table.hline(),
  ),
)

The learned weights reach 0.350 on train but only 0.330 on test, a two-game wobble over the sum
baseline (0.310) that is well within sampling noise on 100 games. An optimal linear combination of
every available feature, fit on 965 games, delivers no robust top-1 gain on held-out data. The
re-ranker does robustly help recall/MRR (the part that generalises), confirming once more that the
bottleneck is the 31 recall-dead games, not the scorer.

= Conclusions and Limitations

A minimal system -- a typed, pattern-conditioned PPMI graph over PAISÀ, enriched with $approx$18.5k
curated idiom edges, scored by a flat PPMI-sum -- reaches #strong[accuracy\@1 0.31 / MRR 0.38] on
EVALITA 2018 NLP4FUN. It has no learned parameters and a single tuned scalar (the idiom weight,
on a wide plateau). Against it we measured knowledge-graph embeddings, PageRank, noun-restriction,
breadth-aware scorers, three corpus joins, compound / embedding-similarity / Wiktionary /
ConceptNet edges, and a learned re-ranker. The result is unambiguous and repeated across roughly
eight independent experiments: #strong[every extension improves recall, MRR, and acc\@{10,100},
but none improves accuracy\@1.] The curated idiom edges, the purest register match, are the
only lever that ever moved top-1.

#strong[Limitations.]
+ The heuristic decompounder and the nominal-only idiom filter miss verb-initial compounds and verbal idioms.
+ The real ceiling is #emph[recall]: 31 of 100 test games have gold answers that exist as graph nodes but
  lack the clue→ answer edges the corpus patterns cannot produce. Of these, $approx$18 are dictionary-MWE gaps,
  $approx$9 are cultural/proper-noun knowledge, and 2 are vocabulary gaps. Closing them requires a
  #emph[register-matched, associative phrase resource] keyed on co-occurrence #emph[presence],
  not a smarter ranker, more generic text, or paradigmatic similarity, all of which were shown to be dead ends.
  That resource is the one direction with demonstrated acc\@1 headroom and the natural next step.

